article.headline: Cummings scores 12 for UCLA
article.story: SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) -- UCLA coach Ben Howland swallowed hard as Washington State's Thomas Kelati arched a 3-point shot that clanged off the rim in the final second, but the Bruins knew this one was in the bag. "Thank God that kid missed that last shot, or we'd still be out there playing," Howland said after UCLA got past a determined Washington State 48-45 at the Spokane Arena on Thursday night. T.J. Cummings scored 12 points to lead the Bruins to victory. They are now undefeated in Pacific-10 Conference play. "Our guys expected to win," Howland said. "We expected to win those two home games and we expected to win tonight. But as long as Dick Bennett is coach here, it's going to be a very difficult win." Bennett, the Washington State coach, admitted he made a mistake when he called for a zone defense in the final minute, which the Bruins broke. "I went to a zone at the end. I thought it might catch them by surprise and it didn't," Bennett said. "They played it smart and dumped it inside." "It was a great win for us," Howland said. "We were very fortunate to come out of here with a win. The bottom line is, they shot 37 percent and we outscored them by 3." Dijon Thompson, who scored 11 points, sank a pair of free throws in the final seconds to ice the win. The Bruins (7-3, 3-0 Pac-10) were unable to shake the Cougars, who trailed by a point at the half and hung with UCLA the rest of the way. Washington State (7-6, 1-2) was trying for its first victory over the Bruins since a 67-56 win on Feb. 6, 1993, in Pullman. Cummings also led Bruins rebounders with 8. Washington State took the lead, 42-40, on a 3-pointer by Shami Gill with 5:10 remaining and the teams traded baskets the rest of the way. A layup by Cedric Bozeman with 1:05 remaining put the Bruins up to stay 46-45. UCLA jumped out to a 7-2 lead in a low-scoring first period, then held on for a 20-19 halftime lead. The Bruins, who shot about 43 percent from the floor, got 12 points off turnovers and 15 second chance points to WSU's 2. Marcus Moore led Washington State scoring with 13 points. Chris Schlatter added 11 points. The Cougars shot 37.5 percent from the floor, missing 13 of 17 3-point attempts. The Bruins outrebounded WSU 33-30. The game was played in the Spokane Arena, about 75 miles north of the WSU campus. Bennett said the close loss -- the lowest scoring Pac-10 game involving the Cougars since a 48-45 victory over Oregon in February 1983 -- was disappointing. "We played enough of a game to really have a chance," he said, "and yet we made enough mistakes to keep ourselves from getting it."
